Hard rock loosely defined subgenre rock music that began the mid1960s with the garage psychedelic and blues rock movements typified heavy use aggressive vocals distorted electric guitars bass guitar drums and often accompanied with keyboards Hard rock developed into major form popular music the 1970s with notable bands such ACDC the Who Led Zeppelin Queen Deep Purple Aerosmith Kiss and Van Halen During the 1980s some hard rock bands moved away from their hard rock roots and more towards pop rock while others began return hard rock sound Established bands made comeback the mid1980s and reached commercial peak the 1980s with glam metal bands like Bon Jovi and Def Leppard and the rawer sounds Guns Roses which followed with great success the later part that decade Hard rock began losing popularity with the commercial success hiphop urban pop grunge and later Britpop the 1990s Despite this many postgrunge bands adopted hard rock sound and the 2000s there came renewed interest established bands attempts revival and new hard rock bands that emerged from the garage rock and postpunk revival scenes Out this movement came garage rock bands like the White Stripes the Strokes Interpol and later the Black Keys the 2000s only few hard rock bands from the 1970s and 1980s managed sustain highly successful recording careers Hard rock form loud aggressive rock music The electric guitar often emphasised used with distortion and other effects both rhythm instrument using repetitive riffs with varying degree complexity and solo lead instrument Drumming characteristically focuses driving rhythms strong bass drum and backbeat snare sometimes using cymbals for emphasis The bass guitar works conjunction with the drums occasionally playing riffs but usually providing backing for the rhythm and lead guitars Vocals are often growling raspy involve screaming wailing sometimes high range even falsetto voice Hard rock has sometimes been labelled cock rock for its emphasis overt masculinity and sexuality and because has historically been predominantly performed and consumed men the case its audience particularly white workingclass adolescents the late 1960s the term heavy metal was used interchangeably with hard rock but gradually began used describe music played with even more volume and intensity While hard rock maintained bluesy rock and roll identity including some swing the back beat and riffs that tended outline chord progressions their hooks heavy metals riffs often functioned standalone melodies and had swing them Heavy metal took darker characteristics after Black Sabbaths breakthrough the beginning the 1970s the 1980s developed number subgenres often termed extreme metal some which were influenced hardcore punk and which further differentiated the two styles Despite this differentiation hard rock and heavy metal have existed side side with bands frequently standing the boundary crossing between the genres The roots hard rock can traced back the 1950s particularly electric blues which laid the foundations for key elements such rough declamatory vocal style heavy guitar riffs stringbending bluesscale guitar solos strong beat thick riffladen texture and posturing performances Electric blues guitarists began experimenting with hard rock elements such driving rhythms distorted guitar solos and power chords the 1950s evident the work Memphis blues guitarists such Joe Hill Louis Willie Johnson and particularly Pat Hare who captured grittier nastier more ferocious electric guitar sound records such James Cottons Cotton Crop Blues 1954 Other antecedents include Link Wrays instrumental Rumble 1958 and the surf rock instrumentals Dick Dale such Lets Trippin 1961 and Misirlou 1962 the 1960s American and British blues and rock bands began modify rock and roll adding harder sounds heavier guitar riffs bombastic drumming and louder vocals from electric blues Early forms hard rock can heard the work Chicago blues musicians Elmore James Muddy Waters and Howlin Wolf the Kingsmens version Louie Louie 1963 which made garage rock standard and the songs rhythm and blues influenced British Invasion acts including You Really Got the Kinks 1964 Generation the Who 1965 Shapes Things 1966 the Yardbirds Inside Looking Out 1966 the Animals and Cant Get Satisfaction 1965 the Rolling Stones From the late 1960s became common divide mainstream rock music that emerged from psychedelia into soft and hard rock Soft rock was often derived from folk rock using acoustic instruments and putting more emphasis melody and harmonies contrast hard rock was most often derived from blues rock and was played louder and with more intensity Blues rock acts that pioneered the sound included Cream the Jimi Hendrix Experience and the Jeff Beck Group Cream songs like Feel Free 1966 combined blues rock with pop and psychedelia particularly the riffs and guitar solos Eric Clapton Jimi Hendrix produced form bluesinfluenced psychedelic rock which combined elements jazz blues and rock and roll From 1967 Jeff Beck brought lead guitar new heights technical virtuosity and moved blues rock the direction heavy rock with his band the Jeff Beck Group Dave Davies the Kinks Keith Richards the Rolling Stones Pete Townshend the Who Hendrix Clapton and Beck all pioneered the use new guitar effects like phasing feedback and distortion The Beatles began producing songs the new hard rock style beginning with their 1968 double album The Beatles also known the White Album and with the track Helter Skelter attempted create greater level noise than the Who Stephen Thomas Erlewine AllMusic has referred the protometal roar Helter Skelter while Ian MacDonald called ridiculous with McCartney shrieking weedily against massively tapeechoed backdrop outoftune thrashing Groups that emerged from the American psychedelic scene about the same time included Iron Butterfly MC5 Blue Cheer and Vanilla Fudge San Francisco band Blue Cheer released crude and distorted cover Eddie Cochrans classic Summertime Blues from their 1968 debut album Vincebus Eruptum that outlined much the later hard rock and heavy metal sound The same month Steppenwolf released its selftitled debut album including Born Wild which contained the first lyrical reference heavy metal and helped popularise the style when was used the film Easy Rider 1969 Iron Butterflys InAGaddaDaVida 1968 with its 17minutelong title track using organs and with lengthy drum solo also prefigured later elements the sound the end the decade distinct genre hard rock was emerging with bands like Led Zeppelin who mixed the music early rock bands with more hardedged form blues rock and acid rock their first two albums Led Zeppelin 1969 and Led Zeppelin 1969 and Deep Purple who began progressive rock group 1968 but achieved their commercial breakthrough with their fourth and distinctively heavier album Rock 1970 Also significant was Black Sabbaths Paranoid 1970 which combined guitar riffs with dissonance and more explicit references the occult and elements Gothic horror All three these bands have been seen pivotal the development heavy metal but where metal further accentuated the intensity the music with bands like Judas Priest following Sabbaths lead into territory that was often darker and more menacing hard rock tended continue remain the more exuberant goodtime music the early 1970s the Rolling Stones developed their hard rock sound with Exile Main 1972 Initially receiving mixed reviews according critic Steve Erlewine now generally regarded the Rolling Stones finest album They continued pursue the riffheavy sound albums including Its Only Rock Roll 1974 and Black and Blue 1976 Led Zeppelin began mix elements world and folk music into their hard rock from Led Zeppelin III 1970 and Led Zeppelin 1971 The latter included the track Stairway Heaven which would become the most played song the history albumoriented radio Deep Purple continued define hard rock particularly with their album Machine Head 1972 which included the tracks Highway Star and Smoke the Water 1975 guitarist Ritchie Blackmore left going form Rainbow and after the breakup the band the next year vocalist David Coverdale formed Whitesnake 1970 saw the Who release Live Leeds often seen the archetypal hard rock live album and the following year they released their highly acclaimed album Whos Next which mixed heavy rock with extensive use synthesizers Subsequent albums including Quadrophenia 1973 built this sound before Who Are You 1978 their last album before the death pioneering rock drummer Keith Moon later that year Emerging British acts included Free who released their signature song All Right Now 1970 has received extensive radio airplay both the and After the breakup the band 1973 vocalist Paul Rodgers joined supergroup Bad Company whose eponymous first album 1974 was international hit The mixture hard rock and progressive rock evident the works Deep Purple was pursued more directly bands like Uriah Heep and Argent Scottish band Nazareth released their selftitled dbut album 1971 producing blend hard rock and pop that would culminate their best selling Hair the Dog 1975 which contained the protopower ballad Love Hurts Having enjoyed some national success the early 1970s Queen after the release Sheer Heart Attack 1974 and Night the Opera 1975 gained international recognition with sound that used layered vocals and guitars and mixed hard rock with heavy metal progressive rock and even opera The latter featured the single Bohemian Rhapsody which stayed number one the charts for nine weeks the United States shockrock pioneer Alice Cooper achieved mainstream success with the top five album Schools Out 1972 which was followed the album Billion Dollar Babies 1973 Also 1973 blues rockers Top released their classic album Tres Hombres and Aerosmith produced their eponymous dbut did Southern rockers Lynyrd Skynyrd and protopunk outfit New York Dolls demonstrating the diverse directions being pursued the genre Montrose inclu